title: For Sale:  DPMS AR10 *Loaded*
postcontent: Selling my trusty AR10 "The Hammer" to fund another rifle build. I bought this a few years back, off a guy who said he'd had it for some years and only shot it a few times cuz it was too heavy for him to lug around, using black hills 168gr ammo he claimed 1/4" groups @ 100. He sold it to me with a crappy scope (he told me so) I wasted a box of ammo hoping to sight it in, to no avail. First thing first, I got a new scope, I chose a nightforce shv 4-14 and took it out again, I clearanced the top rail to be able to fit a 56mm obj lense. With some cheap freedom munition 155gr Amax I printed a 3/4" group at 200yds! Freedom 168's tended to open up to about 1.5" and the cheapest stuff at Walmart ZQI 150gr was about baseball sized groups. I don't handload, and I stocked up on freedom since it did so well. After I saw what it would do I added a Lantac dragon 7.62 brake, geissele super dynamic combat trigger, pof roll pin, grip, and the PRS stock. Since I bought it, I've probly sent 200ish rounds through it, and it's never had a single hiccup. Runs really clean too, compared to 223/556 and especially 300blk. I painted it camo with krylon, the paint is wearing in good. If you wanted to remove it denatured alcohol takes it right off, or just paint it to your liking. The price reflects just the rifle, no scope, and no bipod. Scope would run about $1200 and the bipod $200. I will include 1 painted 20rd pmag, as well as 1 box of the 155gr amax, so you can verify, and sight in your scope. Call or text REDACTED. 9 MM Carbine from Hi-Point Firearms.
Hi-Point Firearms of Dayton, Ohio has been distributing the Hi-Point line of pistols and carbines for several years now.
You’ll a lot of good reports about the Hi-Point carbine. Shooters that have them seem to love them.
The stock of the Hi-Point carbine is made of a reinforced polymer.
Great the accuracy and performance. The carbine’s sixteen and one-half inch barrel the performance of 9mm ammo is substantially greater than from a handgun barrel. Also, due to the gun’s heft and the excellent telescoping butt pad, felt recoil is nothing. There is absolutely no pain at all delivered to the shooter’s shoulder. Upon firing, the butt plate has about one-half inch of travel to absorb what little recoil there is. The Hi-Point carbine fires from a closed bolt, and is a straight blowback action.
It is a lot of fun to shoot, and is very easy on recoil. The magazine holds ten rounds, and fits flush with the pistol grip. The charging handle is easy to operate, even for someone with limited hand strength. The Hi-Point would make a very good home defense carbine.The Hi-Point carbine has a very good warranty. It is a lifetime warranty, and follows the weapon, so if you sell it, the next owner gets the same warranty.  Of course, you do not want to file a warranty claim, but I did some research.  They said Hi-Point is great – they do the work and send it back promptly (and fix it right the first time).
The Hi-Point carbine is 100% made in the USA.
